006, the rate of sea ice loss in the Arctic Ocean dropped dramatically year to year, culminating in a then-record low in September 2007 (shown). That dramatic loss rate corresponded to the “negative” phase of the Arctic Dipole, a wind pattern that increased the influx of warm, salty water from the Atlantic northward through the narrow Fram Strait.&lt;/p>;
